The paper deals with interest point detection and matching, which is a common problem in computer vision. The use of convolutional neural networks (CNNs) to implicitly match interest points at detection time suggests that the paper belongs to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of this approach for relative pose estimation, which is a common problem in robotics (cs.RO). The use of CNNs also suggests that the paper may belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. Finally, the paper evaluates performance relative to state-of-the-art alternatives, which suggests that it may also belong to the multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category.
